{
  "doc_id": "51724",
  "text": "Racial influence on the methylome has been reported previously. African Americans are generally at hypomethylated state compared to Caucasians. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] Our cross-sectional LACHY study confirms the previous findings. In the present study, we observed a significant interaction between race and 25(OH)D on global methylation. However this is not unexpected since over 97% of the Caucasians were vitamin D deficient, whereas 66% of African Americans were vitamin D deficient. Whether the difference in global methylation between Caucasians and African Americans were race dependent or vitamin D dependent warrants further investigation. African Americans suffer from disproportionately high rates of cardiovascular disease and cancer. Altered methylome may be one of underlying mechanisms that explain these health disparities.",
